PCA exploits correlation!!

PCA crafts or creates new variables based on correlated numeric columns!

Extract or Select the numeric columns¶

Standardize the numeric features¶

In [26]:
Xsonar = StandardScaler().fit_transform(sonar_features)
In [28]:
Xsonar.shape
Out[28]:
(208, 60)

PCA¶

But we will NOT use the same approach that we have used up to this point.

We will NOT specify the n_components argument to PCA().

Lets see what happens if we use DEFAULT arguments to PCA...meaning we will NOT specify arguments when PCA object is initialized!!

In [33]:
sonar_pca = PCA().fit_transform(Xsonar)

Check the shape

In [32]:
sonar_pca.shape
Out[32]:
(208, 60)

There are as many cols returned as the num of cols in the data!!

We have previously specified n_components just to support simple visualization.

But PCA is capable of giving you MORE than just 2 new variables.

PCA creates as many NEW variables as there are in the original data!!!

In [34]:
type(sonar_pca)
Out[34]:
numpy.ndarray

Convert the sonar_pca to a DataFrame using the naming pattern:

pca01, pca02, pcaN, ...

Use Pandas plotting methods to show the std vs the PCA number.

In [53]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

sonar_pca_df.describe().loc["std"].plot(ax=ax)
ax.set_xlabel("Principal Component")
ax.set_ylabel("Standard Deviation")

plt.show()

High ordeded principle components have smaller variations.

This is by design!!

PCA creates the new vars such that PC01 has the HIGHEST variance.

Then, PCA created PC02 to have the NEXT highest variation.

Then, PCA created PC03 to have the NEXT hight variation.

So on and so on, the variation decreased for each subsequent PC!!!

The max number of PCs equals the number of cols in the data!!!

One more important aspect of the PCs!!

We previously saw that the original 60 numeric cols were correlated.

Lets check the correlation structure of the newly created PCs.

In [55]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots()

sns.heatmap(data=sonar_pca_df.corr(),
            vmax=1, vmin=-1, center=0,
            cmap="coolwarm",
            ax=ax)

plt.show()

PCA is created such that the NEW vars are UNCORRELATED!!

PCA is created such that the LOW NUMBERED PCs have the HIGHEST VARIATION while the HIGHEST NUMBERED PCs have the LOWEST VARIATION!

BUT ALL PCS ARE UNCORRELATED!

Why does this matter?¶

We have used the FIRST TWO PCs to help our visualizations.
